here at Harvard Law School.

00:01:42.840 --> 00:01:46.200
In addition to serving as
a tenured law professor

00:01:46.200 --> 00:01:49.140
and developing research
centers at Syracuse

00:01:49.140 --> 00:01:52.050
and the University of
Kansas School of Law,

00:01:52.050 --> 00:01:55.920
he has worked in tribal
courts and legal systems

00:01:55.920 --> 00:02:00.930
serving as Chief Justice for the
Sac and Fox Nation of Missouri,

00:02:00.930 --> 00:02:05.160
advising the Prairie Band
Potawatomi Nation of Kansas

00:02:05.160 --> 00:02:08.300
and working as attorney
general of the Seneca

00:02:08.300 --> 00:02:10.229
Nation of Indians.

00:02:10.229 --> 00:02:13.890
He's the author of numerous
law review articles.

00:02:13.890 --> 00:02:16.910
He has testified
before the US Congress

00:02:16.910 --> 00:02:19.590
and he has served as an
expert witness in matters

00:02:19.590 --> 00:02:22.580
before US and tribal courts.

00:02:22.580 --> 00:02:26.790
Currently he is a senior adviser
at Dentons, the world's largest

00:02:26.790 --> 00:02:29.040
law firm.

00:02:29.040 --> 00:02:32.660
Rob Porter brings incredible
depth and breadth of knowledge

00:02:32.660 --> 00:02:35.030
to our conversation today.

00:02:35.030 --> 00:02:37.790
This is knowledge developed
through an inspiring legal

00:02:37.790 --> 00:02:39.060
career.

00:02:39.060 --> 00:02:42.380
It is also grounded in
Haudenosaunee understandings

00:02:42.380 --> 00:02:45.920
of nation to nation
relationships.

00:02:45.920 --> 00:02:49.330
The Seneca Nation is one of six
nations of the Haudenosaunee

00:02:49.330 --> 00:02:52.810
Confederacy who came
together under the guidance

00:02:52.810 --> 00:02:55.930
of an individual known
as the peacemaker.

00:02:55.930 --> 00:03:00.470
The peacemakers' leadership and
vision united these nations,

00:03:00.470 --> 00:03:02.510
providing a framework
for the people

00:03:02.510 --> 00:03:06.240
to unite in peace,
power, and righteousness.

00:03:06.240 --> 00:03:10.560
Some of you may be aware
of this form of governance,

00:03:10.560 --> 00:03:12.340
which is often
described in English

00:03:12.340 --> 00:03:15.280
as the great law of peace.

00:03:15.280 --> 00:03:17.220
This form of
governance was in place

00:03:17.220 --> 00:03:21.100
when colonists first
arrived in North America.

00:03:21.100 --> 00:03:24.090
The protocols that
Haudenosaunee people practiced

00:03:24.090 --> 00:03:27.710
among themselves and with
foreign tribal nations

00:03:27.710 --> 00:03:33.560
also shaped their diplomatic
relationships with colonists.

00:03:33.560 --> 00:03:36.540
These protocols later
informed interactions

00:03:36.540 --> 00:03:38.900
with the emerging
United States government

00:03:38.900 --> 00:03:42.730
in the decades following
the Revolutionary War.

00:03:42.730 --> 00:03:46.260
They were critical to the
Treaty of Canandaigua,

00:03:46.260 --> 00:03:49.900
which was signed in 1794.

00:03:49.900 --> 00:03:53.190
This treaty, which reinforced
the nation to nation

00:03:53.190 --> 00:03:57.370
relationship between the United
States and the Six Nations

00:03:57.370 --> 00:04:01.820
remains in effect to this
day, and every November 11th,

00:04:01.820 --> 00:04:04.480
Haudenosaunee
people grab-- gather

00:04:04.480 --> 00:04:08.010
in Canandaigua, New York,
to celebrate and commemorate

00:04:08.010 --> 00:04:10.370
this treaty.

00:04:10.370 --> 00:04:13.976
It is incredibly significant
to Haudenosaunee people.

00:04:13.976 --> 00:04:16.640
It is an agreement that
the people struggled

00:04:16.640 --> 00:04:20.180
to negotiate during the
difficult, tumultuous years

00:04:20.180 --> 00:04:22.560
of the early American republic.

00:04:22.560 --> 00:04:25.360
And it is an agreement
that Haudenosaunee people

00:04:25.360 --> 00:04:30.890
have labored to protect
and enforce ever since.

00:04:30.890 --> 00:04:34.650
When we think of native
peoples and native politics,

00:04:34.650 --> 00:04:37.080
the work we undertake
in the present day

00:04:37.080 --> 00:04:41.170
is always linked to much
longer, larger experiences

00:04:41.170 --> 00:04:42.980
and traditions.

00:04:42.980 --> 00:04:46.370
In the same way that the
ancestors who negotiated treaty

00:04:46.370 --> 00:04:49.640
agreements with colonial
governments did so with an eye

00:04:49.640 --> 00:04:53.270
to the past, to
contemporary circumstances

00:04:53.270 --> 00:04:56.590
and to emerging generations,
so do the people

00:04:56.590 --> 00:04:58.840
at today's gathering.

00:04:58.840 --> 00:05:02.040
And it's very good to
be here with all of you.

00:05:02.040 --> 00:05:04.040
This afternoon
Robert Porter will

00:05:04.040 --> 00:05:09.120
speak to some of the ways legal
advocacy and legal education

00:05:09.120 --> 00:05:11.390
helps us all move forward.

00:05:11.390 --> 00:05:12.396
Rob Porter.

