There are a few tribes
that collect taxes,

00:48:25.490 --> 00:48:28.045
but the basic business
model in the American state

00:48:28.045 --> 00:48:29.420
and federal and
local governments

00:48:29.420 --> 00:48:34.740
is that you tax income, you tax
businesses, you tax property

00:48:34.740 --> 00:48:36.750
and that doesn't exist
within any country

00:48:36.750 --> 00:48:38.850
as a general matter.

00:48:38.850 --> 00:48:43.280
So tribes run
businesses-- casinos

00:48:43.280 --> 00:48:45.950
being the most significant
and prominent--

00:48:45.950 --> 00:48:50.250
but could be a grocery store,
could be a gas station.

00:48:50.250 --> 00:48:52.737
-In terms of natural
resources like wood or timber,

00:48:52.737 --> 00:48:54.570
what do you think that
would factor into it?

00:48:54.570 --> 00:48:56.778
-Well, I think that there's
an increasing recognition

00:48:56.778 --> 00:48:59.120
that renewables are better.

00:48:59.120 --> 00:49:02.270
There are many that
don't have renewables

00:49:02.270 --> 00:49:03.950
and much of their
economy sometimes

00:49:03.950 --> 00:49:09.330
is based upon hard rock
mining and other business

00:49:09.330 --> 00:49:11.660
activity that exists really
everywhere in the world.

00:49:11.660 --> 00:49:14.290
My nation for many,
many years probably

00:49:14.290 --> 00:49:17.857
was kept afloat by gravel
mining in our territory.

00:49:17.857 --> 00:49:19.690
And eventually we've
had some recent debates

00:49:19.690 --> 00:49:21.815
over moratorium on that
because we just don't think

00:49:21.815 --> 00:49:23.950
we should be doing it anymore.

00:49:23.950 --> 00:49:29.300
So sovereignty sometimes
manifests itself in behaviors

00:49:29.300 --> 00:49:32.680
that you may not
like, but a tribe

00:49:32.680 --> 00:49:34.820
has authority with respect
to its own territory

00:49:34.820 --> 00:49:36.920
to do what it sees
best for itself

00:49:36.920 --> 00:49:38.960
and that may include
that kind of development.

00:49:38.960 --> 00:49:39.620
-Thank you.

00:49:39.620 --> 00:49:40.120
-Sure.

00:49:42.491 --> 00:49:42.990
-Hi.

00:49:42.990 --> 00:49:44.050
I'm Anne Flaherty.

00:49:44.050 --> 00:49:46.760
I teach political science
at Merrimack College,

00:49:46.760 --> 00:49:48.420
and I also grew up
in upstate New York

00:49:48.420 --> 00:49:53.020
and watched the 1992
conflict unfold.

00:49:53.020 --> 00:49:55.630
So I was glad that
you mentioned it.

00:49:55.630 --> 00:49:57.860
But in recent years,
the state of New York

00:49:57.860 --> 00:50:00.390
has gone back to
attempting to assert

00:50:00.390 --> 00:50:03.065
its right to tax cigarette
sales on reservations.

00:50:03.065 --> 00:50:04.190
And it's not just New York.

00:50:04.190 --> 00:50:05.920
It's other states, too.

00:50:05.920 --> 00:50:10.700
So my question was, how
can states and tribes

00:50:10.700 --> 00:50:13.830
forge a more
cooperative relationship

00:50:13.830 --> 00:50:17.400
when there is ongoing
conflicts like that?

00:50:17.400 --> 00:50:19.980
-Well, it depends on
finding good-hearted folks,

00:50:19.980 --> 00:50:22.560
good-minded folks within
the state government.

00:50:22.560 --> 00:50:27.110
And again, in an effort to
solve problems-- sometimes

00:50:27.110 --> 00:50:28.840
it's just ignorance.

00:50:28.840 --> 00:50:34.100
And in the way dollars flow,
rarely in a tribal nation

00:50:34.100 --> 00:50:36.700
does the dollar
flow more than once.

00:50:36.700 --> 00:50:38.910
It comes in, and
then it's immediately

00:50:38.910 --> 00:50:42.370
leaving the territory,
grocery store, car dealership,

00:50:42.370 --> 00:50:43.600
or whatever.

00:50:43.600 --> 00:50:46.440
And when you realize that if
we did that in my nation--

00:50:46.440 --> 00:50:48.990
we did an economic study
and we demonstrated that

00:50:48.990 --> 00:50:51.099
through direct employment,
through contractors,

00:50:51.099 --> 00:50:52.640
and through other
economic stimulus--

00:50:52.640 --> 00:50:54.985
we were contributing
over a billion dollars

00:50:54.985 --> 00:50:58.120
to the regional economy, which
is an awful lot of non-Indians

00:50:58.120 --> 00:51:00.040
who became taxpayers.

00:51:00.040 --> 00:51:03.980
A non-Indian employee at the
casino who has enough money

00:51:03.980 --> 00:51:06.410
to buy a house is
paying property taxes,

00:51:06.410 --> 00:51:08.380
they're paying sales
tax on their purchases,

00:51:08.380 --> 00:51:11.420
they're paying tax on their
income because they have a job.

00:51:11.420 --> 00:51:13.590
And I think for a
lot of folks that I

00:51:13.590 --> 00:51:16.290
saw from the time I was
first in tribal office

00:51:16.290 --> 00:51:18.930
in the early '90s--
just a dozen years

00:51:18.930 --> 00:51:22.140
later when we had the
casinos-- educating these folks

00:51:22.140 --> 00:51:25.080
and making them
realize, it's a win-win.

00:51:25.080 --> 00:51:28.730
Every time a tribal nation has
land that's not subject to tax

00:51:28.730 --> 00:51:31.949
and turns it into something
productive, it helps everybody.

00:51:31.949 --> 00:51:33.990
And I think that's the
path forward, is hopefully

00:51:33.990 --> 00:51:36.320
finding good-minded,
good-hearted folks in state

00:51:36.320 --> 00:51:39.080
government who can appreciate
that it's a win-win.

00:51:39.080 --> 00:51:39.761
-Thank you.

00:51:39.761 --> 00:51:40.260
-Sure.

00:51:42.490 --> 00:51:42.990
-Hi.

00:51:42.990 --> 00:51:44.590
My name's Leland
Pacheco Morrill.

00:51:44.590 --> 00:51:47.480
I'm Navajo and Santo
Domingo pueblo.

00:51:47.480 --> 00:51:51.040
And I kind of want to address
the Cobell Agreement which

00:51:51.040 --> 00:51:54.850
also is-- kind of supersedes
the land buyback program,

00:51:54.850 --> 00:51:57.150
which is part of the
Dawes Act, which is what?

00:51:57.150 --> 00:51:58.670
120 years ago?

00:51:58.670 --> 00:51:59.950
150 years ago?

00:51:59.950 --> 00:52:04.650
And then also, the Nebraska
versus Parker where the Omaha

00:52:04.650 --> 00:52:05.770
Tribe did actually win.

00:52:05.770 --> 00:52:08.900
But that was actually
based on alcohol tax,

00:52:08.900 --> 00:52:11.710
and then it was
redrawing the lines

00:52:11.710 --> 00:52:16.070
of the actual property of a
reservation system in Nebraska.

00:52:16.070 --> 00:52:20.690
Now each one-- both of those
aspects of it-- one of them

00:52:20.690 --> 00:52:24.650
is to try to reconnect
fractionated lands.

00:52:24.650 --> 00:52:26.595
And the only reason why
I even know about this

00:52:26.595 --> 00:52:29.900
is because the Navajo tribe
actually came to Los Angeles,

00:52:29.900 --> 00:52:31.530
to an urban setting,
to actually talk

00:52:31.530 --> 00:52:35.600
to natives in Los Angeles
regarding the land buyback

00:52:35.600 --> 00:52:37.970
program because so
many of them owned land

00:52:37.970 --> 00:52:40.000
on a reservation
they don't live in.

00:52:40.000 --> 00:52:44.610
And so, but-- but the
land buyback program

00:52:44.610 --> 00:52:51.340
is-- was introduced kind of
to give back an economy, back

00:52:51.340 --> 00:52:53.900
to fractionated land.

00:52:53.900 --> 00:52:57.060
But also then, you have
the Nevad-- Nebraska Parker

00:52:57.060 --> 00:52:59.120
case that was trying
to take away land.

00:52:59.120 --> 00:53:02.589
Do have any comments
on those at all?

00:53:02.589 --> 00:53:04.130
-I feel like this
is kind of Jeopardy

00:53:04.130 --> 00:53:09.060
where I'm getting asked, please
form your answer in a question.

00:53:09.060 --> 00:53:10.280
[LAUGHING]

00:53:10.280 --> 00:53:14.550
-You have touched upon a
whole array of after affects

00:53:14.550 --> 00:53:16.450
of, again, the
colonization agenda.

00:53:16.450 --> 00:53:18.190
All these fractionated
reservations

00:53:18.190 --> 00:53:20.400
and all these divided
land interests,

00:53:20.400 --> 00:53:22.550
and it's really pretty
straightforward.

00:53:22.550 --> 00:53:24.250
You can't really
do much with land

00:53:24.250 --> 00:53:26.440
that you don't have
jurisdiction over.

00:53:26.440 --> 00:53:28.890
So the current
administration really

00:53:28.890 --> 00:53:32.260
should get a lot of applause
for channeling resources

00:53:32.260 --> 00:53:35.070
into reacquiring, allowing
tribes to reacquire

00:53:35.070 --> 00:53:36.850
these lands within
their territory,

00:53:36.850 --> 00:53:38.350
so they can self-govern
and they can

00:53:38.350 --> 00:53:40.460
find a find a way to--
but it's a long process.

00:53:40.460 --> 00:53:44.340
I mean, in some cases you have
hundreds of ostensible owners

00:53:44.340 --> 00:53:45.720
of parcels of land.

00:53:45.720 --> 00:53:47.770
And on two occasions,
the Supreme Court

00:53:47.770 --> 00:53:50.520
has invalidated
efforts by the Congress

00:53:50.520 --> 00:53:53.170
to allow the lands to
be consolidated back

00:53:53.170 --> 00:53:55.170
into the power of the tribe.

00:53:55.170 --> 00:53:56.410
So it's a very hard thing.

00:53:56.410 --> 00:53:59.490
But it also raises a bigger
question which might be,

00:53:59.490 --> 00:54:01.850
where-- what's the source
of economic opportunity

00:54:01.850 --> 00:54:02.730
for tribal nations?

00:54:02.730 --> 00:54:05.520
I was literally at a
conference a couple of days ago

00:54:05.520 --> 00:54:07.680
having a conversation
with a tribal leader

00:54:07.680 --> 00:54:10.590
and I said, "Well, you
realize that the income earned

00:54:10.590 --> 00:54:13.490
by a tribal government
anywhere in America,

00:54:13.490 --> 00:54:17.780
including off territory,
is immune from income tax?"

00:54:17.780 --> 00:54:20.000
Didn't know that.

00:54:20.000 --> 00:54:22.880
So what that means is that
there are potential business

00:54:22.880 --> 00:54:26.850
opportunities for a tribal
nation off territory

00:54:26.850 --> 00:54:30.190
for which at minimum,
there's no income tax

00:54:30.190 --> 00:54:31.740
for the benefit of the tribe.

00:54:31.740 --> 00:54:33.930
That's a pretty
significant advantage

00:54:33.930 --> 00:54:35.534
in relation to other businesses.

00:54:35.534 --> 00:54:37.200
So I think your
question is a great one.

00:54:37.200 --> 00:54:39.610
It's an unbelievably
complicated issue,

00:54:39.610 --> 00:54:41.110
but there are
efforts as you since

00:54:41.110 --> 00:54:42.948
heard about how to solve it.

00:54:42.948 --> 00:54:43.904
OK.

00:54:43.904 --> 00:54:44.811
Yeah?

00:54:44.811 --> 00:54:45.310
-Hi.

00:54:45.310 --> 00:54:46.530
My name is Karina Kesserwan.

00:54:46.530 --> 00:54:48.320
I'm a lawyer in Quebec, Canada.

00:54:48.320 --> 00:54:51.980
And you talk about treaties
and interpretation of treaties

00:54:51.980 --> 00:54:53.456
and jurisdiction over treaties.

00:54:53.456 --> 00:54:55.080
And I'd like to know
if in your opinion

00:54:55.080 --> 00:54:58.684
a treaty can be later appealed
by one of the parties.

00:55:05.020 --> 00:55:10.115
-Well I think, I mean the answer
is yes because it's a treaty.

00:55:10.115 --> 00:55:11.780
It's an agreement.

00:55:11.780 --> 00:55:15.280
And it isn't necessarily that we
like Lone Wolf versus Hitchcock

00:55:15.280 --> 00:55:17.700
which says that you can
abrogate an Indian treaty.

00:55:17.700 --> 00:55:19.750
But my own people
seriously debated that

00:55:19.750 --> 00:55:21.390
during our '92 war.

00:55:21.390 --> 00:55:25.825
Should we actually go back
to pre-treaty conditions?

00:55:25.825 --> 00:55:26.325
Warfare.

00:55:29.610 --> 00:55:31.742
You know, it was a debate,
and we didn't do it.

00:55:31.742 --> 00:55:33.200
And there-- but
there was actually,

00:55:33.200 --> 00:55:35.660
what would happen if we did?

00:55:35.660 --> 00:55:37.260
And so I don't know
if there'll ever

00:55:37.260 --> 00:55:39.760
be circumstances in the
future where that matters,

00:55:39.760 --> 00:55:42.070
but it's an agreement.

00:55:42.070 --> 00:55:44.360
And I suppose if you really
take agreements seriously,

00:55:44.360 --> 00:55:47.565
you have to respect the
sovereignty of both governments

00:55:47.565 --> 00:55:48.190
to that treaty.

00:55:53.251 --> 00:55:53.750
-Rob.

00:55:53.750 --> 00:55:54.610
Thank you so much.

00:55:54.610 --> 00:55:55.210
That was fantastic.

00:55:55.210 --> 00:55:55.510
Thank you.

00:55:55.510 --> 00:55:56.135
That was great.

